			<article class="post-2067 post type-post status-publish hentry category-dealbook" id="post-2067">
                        <div class="visually-hidden">
                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Credit Suisse Names New Chief</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Sydney Ember                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-03-10T11:26:38+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">March 10, 2015 7:26 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">March 10, 2015 7:26 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/10/morning-agenda-credit-suisse-names-new-chief/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Credit Suisse Names New Chief" data-description="Credit Suisse is replacing its longstanding leader. | The Simon Property Group bids for a rival. | Banks are no longer financing certain coal-mining companies. | The tech blog Gigaom has shut down.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>CREDIT SUISSE NAMES NEW CHIEF</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Brady W. Dougan is stepping down as chief executive of Credit Suisse, the bank said on Tuesday, ending his tenure as one of the longest-serving chieftains of a global banking powerhouse, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/10/business/dealbook/credit-suisse-chief-said-to-be-set-to-step-down.html?ref=dealbook">Jessica Silver-Greenberg and Jenny Anderson write in DealBook</a>. Mr. Dougan â an American who has led the Swiss bank since before the financial crisis and has been called âthe Teflon manâ for his ability to deflect troublesome issues â will be succeeded by Tidjane Thiam, who heads the British insurance company Prudential, where he has been praised for his leadership.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The change at Credit Suisse is effective in June and <b>follows recent stumbles</b>, Ms. Silver-Greenberg and Ms. Anderson write. Last year, the Zurich-based bank, which has large operations in New York, was the first of its size and significance in decades to plead guilty to a criminal charge. In that settlement with United States authorities, Credit Suisse admitted that its bankers enabled clients to illegally evade American taxes, and agreed to pay about $2.6 billion in penalties. Mr. Dougan could have survived the legal problems if the bankâs financial performance had been better, said people briefed on the matter. The bank has prepared investors for continued fallout from the legal settlements.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Thiam, who was born in the Ivory Coast, became the first Ivorian to pass the entrance examination to the exclusive Ãcole Polytechnique in Paris. He received an M.B.A. from Insead, the business school, in 1988 and then worked for McKinsey, the consulting firm, in New York and Paris. In the early 1990s, he returned to his country and eventually became the minister for planning and development. He was named chief executive of Prudential in 2009, becoming the first black chief executive of a F.T.S.E. 100 company.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shares of Credit Suisse <a href="//on.ft.com/1GkMeLN">jumped in early morning trading</a> on the news of the leadership change, while Prudentialâs fell. Analysts responded positively as well, with one <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-03-10/credit-suisse-names-prudential-s-thiam-as-ceo-to-replace-dougan">telling Bloomberg Business</a>: âThiam will bring some fresh air to Credit Suisse, albeit without the banking background.â Before the announcement, Sally Yim, vice president at Moodyâs Investors Service, <a href="//www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/10/us-credit-suisse-gp-ceo-dougan-idUSKBN0M601320150310">told Reuters</a>: âCredit Suisse has had different issues throughout the years and someone with a diverse background could look at its strategy with a fresh pair of eyes.â</p>
