<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>MALL OWNER BIDS FOR RIVAL</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Simon Property Group, which owns malls like the Forum Shops at the Caesars Palace Las Vegas, began an unsolicited attempt on Monday to acquire a rival, the Macerich Company, in a quest to consolidate its hold on high-end shopping malls, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/10/business/dealbook/mall-operator-simon-property-makes-22-4-billion-hostile-bid-for-macerich.html">DealBookâs David Gelles writes</a>. Simonâs offer values Macerich at about $22.4 billion, including the assumption of some $6.4 billion of Macerichâs debt. Simonâs chief executive, David Simon, said he was making his offer public after unsuccessfully trying to get Macerichâs management to engage in talks about a sale since December.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Gelles writes: âThe backdrop for Mr. Simonâs ambitions is an <b>increasingly polarized retail landscape</b>. While lower- and middle-class shoppers are seeking bargains and avoiding traditional shopping centers, high-end malls are booming.â Simon, based in Indianapolis, is already the biggest operator of so-called Class A malls. Adding Macerichâs portfolio of properties would make Simon even bigger, expanding its reach in California and other Western states. Macerich, which is incorporated in Maryland but run out of California, also operates Class A malls and shopping centers, but does not compete with Simon in many markets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a move to <b>ease antitrust concerns</b>, Simon said it had reached a deal to sell some Macerich assets to General Growth Properties. Details of the sale to General Growth were not made public, but a person briefed on the matter said Simon planned to sell just a handful properties, worth less than 25 percent of the value of Macerichâs portfolio. Macerich said on Monday that it had received Simonâs offer and was reviewing the proposal with its advisers. It is unlikely that Macerich will simply accept Simonâs offer, Mr. Gelles writes. Instead, it could hold out for a higher price. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Simon has offered equal parts cash and stock worth $91 for each unit of Macerich stock, or about $16 billion. That represents a 30 percent premium to Macerichâs share price before Simon announced it had acquired a 3.6 percent toehold in the company in November.</p>
